movements easy to trace.

43:16.042 --> 43:19.510
He's significantly north of the
Arctic Circle in the summertime

43:19.512 --> 43:24.481
and then he moves south as
the weather gets colder.

43:24.483 --> 43:29.286
I'm still not seeing the evidence.
Where's the evidence?

43:29.288 --> 43:33.490
All right, all right,
let's start with Iqaluit.

43:33.492 --> 43:37.294
Since they began keeping records
in the early 20th century,

43:37.296 --> 43:41.198
they've recorded 112 homicides,
and 41 disappearances.

43:41.200 --> 43:43.934
Now, based on the population size,

43:43.936 --> 43:45.903
and the time span
of over 100 years,

43:45.905 --> 43:48.472
that's statistically
a little bit high.

43:48.474 --> 43:52.877
But it's not anything that you'd
find outside of a normal bell curve.

43:52.879 --> 43:57.081
However, when you look
at unexplained homicides

43:57.083 --> 43:59.984
and disappearances,
the number is 44.

43:59.986 --> 44:03.153
Of those 44 homicides
and disappearances,

44:03.155 --> 44:07.391
42 of them occurred
between April and May.

44:07.393 --> 44:10.394
Bear Lake, that's few
hundred miles to the south.

44:10.396 --> 44:12.930
Unexplained homicides
and disappearances, 20.

44:12.932 --> 44:16.166
Of those 17, between
February and March.

44:16.168 --> 44:19.069
Yellowknife. Unexplained homicides
and disappearances, 74.

44:19.071 --> 44:22.072
65 of them occurring between
December and February.

44:22.074 --> 44:23.274
You see what I'm saying.

44:23.276 --> 44:28.379
These statistical anomalies,
these spikes in murders,

44:28.381 --> 44:31.548
they follow a migratory pattern.

44:31.550 --> 44:35.119
They're moving as the
creature would move.

44:35.121 --> 44:39.556
So you're saying the thing
is a serial killer?

44:39.558 --> 44:41.191
Oh. No, no.

44:41.193 --> 44:44.161
If he was intent on killing humans

44:44.163 --> 44:47.231
the numbers would be astronomical.

44:47.233 --> 44:53.137
I think these attacks are a matter
of self-preservation, that's all.

44:53.405 --> 44:54.939
They're, um...

44:54.941 --> 44:59.643
They're the creature trying to protect
his anonymity, his territory.

44:59.645 --> 45:02.346
All right, all right, fuck this.
Sorry.

45:02.348 --> 45:03.714
What's wrong?

45:03.716 --> 45:05.983
This whole thing is fucked.

45:05.985 --> 45:08.118
Oh, okay, now you believe me.

45:08.120 --> 45:11.989
No, I still think your theory
is complete horseshit.

45:11.991 --> 45:14.058
This is not funny anymore.

45:14.060 --> 45:15.492
I think you knew what
you were getting into

45:15.494 --> 45:17.394
when you came in the
crew and signed up.

45:17.396 --> 45:19.296
Hey, you're overreacting.

45:19.298 --> 45:20.731
We're sitting right here.

45:20.733 --> 45:22.599
I'm not fucking doing this.
Are you kidding me?

45:22.601 --> 45:24.034
Excuse me.

45:24.036 --> 45:27.338
The last time I checked, I was
paying you, isn't that right?

45:27.340 --> 45:30.574
And I'm still paying you.
I'm paying you and you.

45:30.576 --> 45:32.443
Everybody here, I'm paying.

45:32.445 --> 45:35.446
So I say when somebody leaves
and somebody doesn't leave.

45:35.448 --> 45:37.314
It's me who's running this ship.

45:37.316 --> 45:40.150
And if I want advice from a
sound man, I will ask you.

45:40.152 --> 45:41.986
Hey, hey, hey, hey!

45:41.988 --> 45:44.722
Stop it! Enough. Enough.

45:44.724 --> 45:49.026
Brian! Good Lord!
You are both overreacting.

45:49.028 --> 45:50.627
Enough!

45:56.034 --> 45:57.768
Sorry.

46:00.305 --> 46:02.539
I'm sorry.

46:02.541 --> 46:03.640
Okay? I'm sorry.

46:03.642 --> 46:08.345
Jonathan, I didn't mean to
say your theory is bullshit.

46:08.347 --> 46:12.683
It's really scary, where we are.

46:12.685 --> 46:17.187
We are out by ourselves, this
is really not what I'm used to.

46:17.189 --> 46:20.124
So, I'm sorry.

46:20.126 --> 46:21.592
I'm sorry, too.

46:21.594 --> 46:25.729
Boys, why don't you
have a swig of this?

46:25.731 --> 46:28.232
You won't find this
in the lower 48.

46:34.205 --> 46:35.439
Can I have some?

46:35.441 --> 46:37.408
Thank you, Karl.

46:41.446 --> 46:44.681
No hard feelings. Jonathan?

46:44.683 --> 46:46.583
No hard feelings?

46:52.724 --> 46:56.093
Karl, what do you think
of Jonathan's theory,

46:56.095 --> 46:58.195
about the crime clusters?

47:00.632 --> 47:03.767
It makes sense.

47:03.769 --> 47:07.704
A predator after the caribou herd.

47:07.706 --> 47:12.376
Something that would also kill a
human if it happened upon one.

47:12.378 --> 47:15.579
Wow. So you believe him?

47:15.581 --> 47:18.315
Well, the theory is dead-on.
The culprit's wrong.

47:20.518 --> 47:22.319
What do you mean?

47:22.321 --> 47:24.855
He's mistaken
Frankenstein for a bear.

47:28.260 --> 47:30.094
They kill at least a
few people every year,

47:30.096 --> 47:32.830
probably more than
what gets reported.

47:32.832 --> 47:38.135
I guess that would explain all the
unsolved murders and disappearances.

47:39.337 --> 47:42.106
But I don't know, I ain't
done the research.

47:42.108 --> 47:44.708
And you seem like a smart guy.

47:44.710 --> 47:46.610
I bagged a lot of
big game in my day.

47:46.612 --> 47:49.513
I wouldn't mind bagging
myself a Frankenstein.

47:57.455 --> 47:59.256
God! Fuck.

47:59.258 --> 48:00.357
Fuck.

48:00.359 --> 48:01.792
Yeah.

48:01.794 --> 48:06.363
I'll tell you one thing, polar
bear, best damn hunter on Earth.

48:06.365 --> 48:11.635
Tigers and lions are just pussies
by comparison, literally.

48:11.637 --> 48:12.870
Figuratively.

48:12.872 --> 48:15.906
Polar bear can outrun a racehorse.

48:15.908 --> 48:19.243
Can swim in ice cold water
for 100 kilometers.

48:19.245 --> 48:22.346
Hold his breath underwater
for 15 minutes.

48:22.348 --> 48:23.514
You ever seen one?

48:23.516 --> 48:26.917
Hell, I've killed 12 of them.

48:26.919 --> 48:30.854
Friend of mine, I used to
hunt with, Ted Meachum.

48:30.856 --> 48:34.424
He survived a polar bear attack.

48:34.426 --> 48:37.761
He's north of Churchill,
that's in Manitoba.

48:37.763 --> 48:42.199
Took some weekend warriors
up on a hunt, 1992.

48:43.935 --> 48:46.503
I had a bad feeling about that.

48:46.505 --> 48:51.275
The winter was mild, ice didn't
freeze over till February.

48:51.277 --> 48:55.212
When it did, it was
only for a few weeks.

48:55.214 --> 48:59.650
The polar bears eat seals.

48:59.652 --> 49:03.520
When the Hudson isn't frozen
over, they can't hunt seals.

49:03.522 --> 49:08.592
When they can't hunt seals,
they hunt something else.

49:08.594 --> 49:11.695
Anyway, old Ted took 'em
out on a light plane.

49:11.697 --> 49:14.565
They had engine trouble,
had to put down.

49:14.567 --> 49:17.968
Six men stranded in the tundra.

49:17.970 --> 49:22.206
A big male polar bear
got the bead on them.

49:22.208 --> 49:23.874
Pulled one man out of the fuselage

49:23.876 --> 49:26.677
in the middle of the
night, screaming.

49:28.980 --> 49:31.982
Dragged another through the ice.

49:31.984 --> 49:34.952
Come daylight they
thought they were safe.

49:34.954 --> 49:38.222
Polar bears, like most
predators, prefer the ambush,

49:38.224 --> 49:40.224
not this one, he was different.

49:40.226 --> 49:42.659
He attacked that plane dead on.

49:42.661 --> 49:44.995
Ripped apart what was
left of the fuselage,

49:44.997 --> 49:48.398
killed all the
remaining passengers.

49:48.400 --> 49:50.934
All except Ted.

49:50.936 --> 49:53.971
What happened to Ted?

49:53.973 --> 49:56.707
That's the damnedest thing.

49:56.709 --> 50:00.510
He ripped off Ted's leg.
I mean, just ripped it off.

50:00.512 --> 50:04.748
Ate it in front of him.
But let him live.

50:04.750 --> 50:09.386
Like he was toying with him.

50:09.388 --> 50:11.822
Ted was supposed to
be gone overnight.

50:11.824 --> 50:16.627
So the following day I
led a search party.

50:16.629 --> 50:18.929
Got a sea plane.
Spotted the wreckage.

50:18.931 --> 50:22.766
Found Ted nearly bled to death.

50:22.768 --> 50:26.770
But he did a good job
with the tourniquet.

50:26.772 --> 50:30.507
I guess the bear did get
him in the end though.

50:30.509 --> 50:31.842
What do you mean?

50:31.844 --> 50:34.311
He was never right
after the attack.

50:34.313 --> 50:38.915
Six months later, he shot himself
in the head with his Winchester.

50:41.419 --> 50:43.053
That's fucked up.

50:43.055 --> 50:46.757
Yeah. Don't fuck with
the forces of nature.

50:48.826 --> 50:53.330
You better respect her, because
nature doesn't forgive.

50:57.869 --> 50:59.736
Are you fucking with us?

51:02.073 --> 51:04.708
Do I look like I'm
fucking with you?

51:10.548 --> 51:13.717
Whoa, easy, look.

51:15.887 --> 51:19.056
Hello. Hi, Eric.

51:19.058 --> 51:22.025
Kiss me, I want a kiss.
I want a kiss, Eric.

51:22.027 --> 51:23.994
Brian, that's disgusting.

51:26.497 --> 51:28.365
Let me see that.

51:36.574 --> 51:38.775
He's out there, you know.

51:38.777 --> 51:41.478
And tomorrow we'll
go looking for him.

51:41.480 --> 51:43.513
But right now, I'm turning in.

51:43.515 --> 51:44.981
Now, if those wolves start up,

51:44.983 --> 51:49.486
don't you go waking me up.
I'll make good on my promise.

51:49.488 --> 51:51.455
Okay.

52:15.646 --> 52:17.781
Those wolves are really
freaking me out.

52:17.783 --> 52:19.950
I know.

52:19.952 --> 52:21.485
They sound closer than last night.

52:21.487 --> 52:23.387
I know.

52:23.389 --> 52:25.689
Jesus Christ.

52:25.691 --> 52:28.959
Something's got them worked up.

52:28.961 --> 52:31.395
I don't know how he
sleeps through this.

52:31.397 --> 52:32.829
Karl?

52:32.831 --> 52:35.499
This is like a lullaby to him.

52:35.501 --> 52:37.968
Shh, shh! Listen.

52:39.771 --> 52:41.938
What?

52:41.940 --> 52:44.141
They just stopped.

52:47.512 --> 52:50.080
Maybe now we can get some sleep.

52:55.520 --> 52:57.087
What was that?

52:57.089 --> 52:58.989
Holy shit!

52:58.991 --> 53:00.190
Should we wake up Karl?

53:00.192 --> 53:04.594
No! We should... No. He'll kill me.

53:04.596 --> 53:06.129
I think that's him.

53:06.131 --> 53:08.098
What? Really? You think so?

53:08.100 --> 53:09.433
Yes.

53:09.435 --> 53:10.567
No way.

53:10.569 --> 53:13.837
Yes, I do. The wolves are scared
of him. That's why they stopped.

53:13.839 --> 53:15.672
It's a bear.

53:15.674 --> 53:16.907
I don't think so.

53:16.909 --> 53:18.875
Have you ever heard a
bear howl at night?

53:18.877 --> 53:20.577
Do you know what it sounds like?

53:20.579 --> 53:23.480
Do you know what it sounds like?

53:23.482 --> 53:26.516
No, but it probably
sounds like that.

53:26.518 --> 53:28.552
Yeah.

53:31.523 --> 53:33.890
That sound like a bear to you?

53:48.139 --> 53:50.841
Somebody stole one of our
snowmobiles last night

53:50.843 --> 53:53.477
and trashed the other one.

53:53.479 --> 53:54.945
The third one is still working.

53:54.947 --> 53:56.780
Oh, terrific.

53:56.782 --> 53:58.148
I thought we were alone out here.

53:58.150 --> 54:00.884
Well, we're obviously not.

54:00.886 --> 54:02.486
Who could have done this?

54:02.488 --> 54:04.254
Somebody was definitely here.

54:04.256 --> 54:06.723
Big fucker, too.

54:06.725 --> 54:09.226
Tracks lead over there.

54:09.228 --> 54:12.229
It's not a polar bear, or a
goddamn monster. It's a man.

54:14.732 --> 54:16.800
Hey, where are you going?

54:16.802 --> 54:18.568
In 30 minutes, I'll have his ass.

54:18.570 --> 54:22.706
He didn't take any fuel, and
those snowmobiles were low...

54:22.708 --> 54:24.708
I don't think you
should go out there.

54:24.710 --> 54:25.942
What did you say?

54:25.944 --> 54:29.246
I said, I don't think you
should go out there.

54:29.248 --> 54:32.582
Are you fucking kidding me?

54:32.584 --> 54:34.117
Karl, I just think it's a bad idea.

54:34.119 --> 54:36.253
Hey!

54:36.255 --> 54:39.055
We got a crisis on
our hands right now.

54:39.057 --> 54:42.826
I need you guys to do
exactly what I say.

54:42.828 --> 54:44.728
No need to panic.
I'll be back soon.

54:44.730 --> 54:46.863
I understand, I don't think
you should go out there.

54:46.865 --> 54:48.832
This is my country!

54:48.834 --> 54:50.133
I'll be goddamned

54:50.135 --> 54:53.803
if I let some motherfucker come
in here and steal my stuff.

54:53.805 --> 54:55.205
All right?

54:58.943 --> 55:00.944
You don't want to take
the other snowmobile?

55:00.946 --> 55:03.980
And let him know I'm coming?
You fucking nuts?

55:15.092 --> 55:18.895
It's been four hours since Karl left
and there's been no sign of him.

55:18.897 --> 55:20.330
So I'm officially worried.

55:20.332 --> 55:22.699
Brian and Eric have volunteered
to go looking for him,

55:22.701 --> 55:24.134
while the rest of us
stay at the camp.

55:24.136 --> 55:25.602
I drive this time.
You film.

55:25.604 --> 55:27.604
You drive like a grandma.

55:31.142 --> 55:34.311
Great fucking trip, Vicky.

55:34.313 --> 55:36.012
We don't make it back,

55:36.014 --> 55:41.017
I want to officially go on tape
as saying this country sucks

55:41.019 --> 55:43.887
and it can lick my balls.

55:43.889 --> 55:47.591
USA rules! Canada can lick 'em.

55:47.593 --> 55:51.161
Just come back in an hour
whether you find Karl or not.

55:51.163 --> 55:53.830
One hour, otherwise
I start to freak out.

55:53.832 --> 55:55.865
An hour, got it. You ready?

55:55.867 --> 55:57.834
